{"title_page": "Peter Abbott", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{For|the footballer|Peter Abbott (footballer)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Sir Peter Abbott\n|image= \n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption=\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1942|02|12|df=yes}}\n|death_date=  {{death date and age|2015|09|28|1942|2|12|df=y}}\n|birth_place= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|nickname= \n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= [[Royal Navy]]\n|serviceyears= 1964\u20132001\n|rank= [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff]]<br/>[[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]<br/>[[Flag Officer, Second Flotilla|Second Flotilla]]<br>{{HMS|Ajax|F114|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Ambuscade|F172|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Chawton|M1209|6}}\n|battles= [[Falklands War]]\n|awards= [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire]]<br/>[[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit|Officer of the Legion of Merit]] (United States)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission|Commissioner of Commonwealth War Graves]]\n}}\n[[Admiral (United Kingdom)|Admiral]] '''Sir Peter Charles Abbott''' {{post-nominals|counrty=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GBE|KCB}} (12 February 1942 \u2013 28 September 2015) was a British naval officer and [[Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff of the United Kingdom.]].\n\n==Early life==\nAbbott was born on 12 February 1942.<ref name=\"Who's Who\">{{cite book|title=Who's who 1998 : an annual biographical dictionary|year=1998|publisher=St. Martin's Press|location=New York|isbn=0312175914|chapter=Abbott, Adm. Sir Peter (Charles)}}</ref> He was educated at [[St. Edward's School, Oxford]] before going on to [[Queens' College, Cambridge]].<ref>[http://www.quns.cam.ac.uk/alumni/2010-events/1960-event Queens' College e-bulletin for the 1960 Anniversary Celebration Invitation Dinner] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607181611/http://www.quns.cam.ac.uk/alumni/2010-events/1960-event |date=7 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nAbbott was [[Commissioned officer|commissioned]] into the [[Royal Navy]] in 1964.<ref name=debrett>[http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/search/results/10741/Peter%20Charles%20ABBOTT.aspx Admiral Sir Peter Abbott] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323204902/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/search/results/10741/Peter%20Charles%20ABBOTT.aspx |date=23 March 2012 }} Debretts</ref> He commanded  the minesweeper, {{HMS|Chawton|M1209|6}}, from 1972 to 1975 and then joined the staff of the Senior Naval Officer in the [[West Indies]].<ref name=debrett/>\n\nHe became commanding officer of the [[frigate]] {{HMS|Ambuscade|F172|6}} in 1976, second-in-command of the aircraft carrier {{HMS|Bulwark|R08|6}} in 1980 and the [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of Defence Staff]]'s briefer during the [[Falklands War]] in 1982.<ref name=debrett/> He then became commanding officer of the frigate {{HMS|Ajax|F114|6}} as well as captain of the [[1st Frigate Squadron (United Kingdom)|1st Frigate Squadron]] in 1983.<ref name=debrett/>\n\nHe became Director of Navy Plans in 1985 and, having been promoted to [[rear admiral]], he was appointed [[Flag Officer, Second Flotilla]] in 1989.<ref name=debrett/> He was made [[Assistant Chief of the Naval Staff]] in 1991 and, having been promoted to [[vice admiral]], was appointed [[Supreme Allied Commander Atlantic|Deputy Supreme Allied Commander Atlantic]] in 1993.<ref name=debrett/> He became [[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]] and, having been promoted to [[admiral]] in 1995, he became [[Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff]] in 1997.<ref name=debrett/>\n\n==Later life==\nIn retirement, Abbott was made [[Chairman]] of the Trustees of the [[Royal Naval Museum]].<ref>[http://www.royalnavalmuseum.org/about_rnmtrustees.htm Royal Naval Museum]</ref> He was also President of [[Marine Society & Sea Cadets|MSSC]], governing charity of the [[Marine Society]] and the [[Sea Cadets]].<ref>[http://www.ms-sc.org/whos-who MSSC \u2013 Who's who]</ref>\n\nHe died of cancer on 28 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/195169/abbott |title=Abbott|date= 4 October 2015|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and decorations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|[[File:Order of the British Empire (Military) Ribbon.png|80px]] || [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire]] (GBE) || 1999<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=55354|supp=y|page=5|date=30 December 1998}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Order of the Bath UK ribbon.png|80px]] || [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] (KCB) || 1994<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=53696|supp=y|page=2|date=10 June 1994}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Us legion of merit officer rib.png|80px]] || [[Legion of Merit|Officer of the Legion of Merit]] || (United States) 1995<ref>Mosley, Charles, editor. Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes. Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hugo White]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Assistant Chief of the Naval Staff]]|years=1991\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Brigstocke]]}}\n|-\n{{succession box| title=[[Supreme Allied Commander Atlantic|Deputy Supreme Allied Commander Atlantic]]| before=[[Peter Woodhead|Sir Peter Woodhead]]| after=[[Ian Garnett|Sir Ian Garnett]] | years=1993\u20131995}}\n|-\n{{succession box|title=[[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]|before=Sir Hugo White|after=[[Michael Boyce, Baron Boyce|Sir Michael Boyce]]|years=1995\u20131997}}\n|-\n{{succession box|title=[[Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff]]|before=[[John Willis (RAF officer)|Sir John Willis]] |after=[[Anthony Bagnall|Sir Anthony Bagnall]]|years=1997\u20132001}}\n|-\n{{s-herald}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Patrick Hine|Sir Patrick Hine]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Arms of the Order of the British Empire]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Fulton (Royal Marines officer)|Sir Robert Fulton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Vice Chiefs of Defence Staff|state=collapsed}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abbott, Peter}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Falklands War]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{For|the footballer|Peter Abbott (footballer)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Sir Peter Abbott\n|image= \n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption=\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1942|02|12|df=yes}}\n|death_date=  {{death date and age|2015|09|28|1942|2|12|df=y}}\n|birth_place= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|nickname= \n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= [[Royal Navy]]\n|serviceyears= 1964\u20132001\n|rank= [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff]]<br/>[[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]<br/>[[Flag Officer, Second Flotilla|Second Flotilla]]<br>{{HMS|Ajax|F114|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Ambuscade|F172|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Chawton|M1209|6}}\n|battles= [[Falklands War]]\n|awards= [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire]]<br/>[[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Legion of Merit|Officer of the Legion of Merit]] (United States)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission|Commissioner of Commonwealth War Graves]]\n}}\n[[Admiral (United Kingdom)|Admiral]] '''Sir Peter Charles Abbott''' {{post-nominals|counrty=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GBE|KCB}} (12 February 1942 \u2013 28 September 2015) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer and [[Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff]].\n\n==Early life==\nAbbott was born on 12 February 1942.<ref name=\"Who's Who\">{{cite book|title=Who's who 1998 : an annual biographical dictionary|year=1998|publisher=St. Martin's Press|location=New York|isbn=0312175914|chapter=Abbott, Adm. Sir Peter (Charles)}}</ref> He was educated at [[St. Edward's School, Oxford]] before going on to [[Queens' College, Cambridge]].<ref>[http://www.quns.cam.ac.uk/alumni/2010-events/1960-event Queens' College e-bulletin for the 1960 Anniversary Celebration Invitation Dinner] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607181611/http://www.quns.cam.ac.uk/alumni/2010-events/1960-event |date=7 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\nAbbott was [[Commissioned officer|commissioned]] into the [[Royal Navy]] in 1964.<ref name=debrett>[http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/search/results/10741/Peter%20Charles%20ABBOTT.aspx Admiral Sir Peter Abbott] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323204902/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/search/results/10741/Peter%20Charles%20ABBOTT.aspx |date=23 March 2012 }} Debretts</ref> He commanded  the minesweeper, {{HMS|Chawton|M1209|6}}, from 1972 to 1975 and then joined the staff of the Senior Naval Officer in the [[West Indies]].<ref name=debrett/>\n\nHe became commanding officer of the [[frigate]] {{HMS|Ambuscade|F172|6}} in 1976, second-in-command of the aircraft carrier {{HMS|Bulwark|R08|6}} in 1980 and the [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of Defence Staff]]'s briefer during the [[Falklands War]] in 1982.<ref name=debrett/> He then became commanding officer of the frigate {{HMS|Ajax|F114|6}} as well as captain of the [[1st Frigate Squadron (United Kingdom)|1st Frigate Squadron]] in 1983.<ref name=debrett/>\n\nHe became Director of Navy Plans in 1985 and, having been promoted to [[rear admiral]], he was appointed [[Flag Officer, Second Flotilla]] in 1989.<ref name=debrett/> He was made [[Assistant Chief of the Naval Staff]] in 1991 and, having been promoted to [[vice admiral]], was appointed [[Supreme Allied Commander Atlantic|Deputy Supreme Allied Commander Atlantic]] in 1993.<ref name=debrett/> He became [[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]] and, having been promoted to [[admiral]] in 1995, he became [[Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff]] in 1997.<ref name=debrett/>\n\n==Later life==\nIn retirement, Abbott was made [[Chairman]] of the Trustees of the [[Royal Naval Museum]].<ref>[http://www.royalnavalmuseum.org/about_rnmtrustees.htm Royal Naval Museum]</ref> He was also President of [[Marine Society & Sea Cadets|MSSC]], governing charity of the [[Marine Society]] and the [[Sea Cadets]].<ref>[http://www.ms-sc.org/whos-who MSSC \u2013 Who's who]</ref>\n\nHe died of cancer on 28 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/195169/abbott |title=Abbott|date= 4 October 2015|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and decorations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|[[File:Order of the British Empire (Military) Ribbon.png|80px]] || [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire]] (GBE) || 1999<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=55354|supp=y|page=5|date=30 December 1998}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Order of the Bath UK ribbon.png|80px]] || [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] (KCB) || 1994<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=53696|supp=y|page=2|date=10 June 1994}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Us legion of merit officer rib.png|80px]] || [[Legion of Merit|Officer of the Legion of Merit]] || (United States) 1995<ref>Mosley, Charles, editor. Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes. Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hugo White]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Assistant Chief of the Naval Staff]]|years=1991\u20131993}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Brigstocke]]}}\n|-\n{{succession box| title=[[Supreme Allied Commander Atlantic|Deputy Supreme Allied Commander Atlantic]]| before=[[Peter Woodhead|Sir Peter Woodhead]]| after=[[Ian Garnett|Sir Ian Garnett]] | years=1993\u20131995}}\n|-\n{{succession box|title=[[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]|before=Sir Hugo White|after=[[Michael Boyce, Baron Boyce|Sir Michael Boyce]]|years=1995\u20131997}}\n|-\n{{succession box|title=[[Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice-Chief of the Defence Staff]]|before=[[John Willis (RAF officer)|Sir John Willis]] |after=[[Anthony Bagnall|Sir Anthony Bagnall]]|years=1997\u20132001}}\n|-\n{{s-herald}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Patrick Hine|Sir Patrick Hine]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Arms of the Order of the British Empire]]|years=2011\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Fulton (Royal Marines officer)|Sir Robert Fulton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Vice Chiefs of Defence Staff|state=collapsed}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abbott, Peter}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Falklands War]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n", "name_user": "ThePhantom65", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup; added detail.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Abbott"}
